\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\sum_{i=1}^{216} x_i^{2}\right) &= \dfrac{107}{215} + \sum_{i=1}^{216} \frac{\dfrac{1}{2^{i}} x_i^{2}}{2(1-\dfrac{1}{2^{i}})}\\
&= \dfrac{107}{215} + \sum_{i=1}^{216} \frac{\dfrac{1}{2^{i}} x_i^{2}}{2(1-\dfrac{1}{2^{i}})}.
\end{align*}
Since this equation holds for all positive real numbers $x_1, x_2, \dots, x_{216}$ such that $\sum_{i=1}^{216} x_i = 1$, we can conclude that the maximum possible value of $x_2$ occurs when $x_1 = x_2 = x_3 = \dots = x_{216} = \frac{1}{216}$.
\end{align*}
